gaps.what:
THE core gap. `res_place_plan` (resources_internal.h:97-106) is a vocabulary with no verb: `owned_alloc_locked` (resources_registry.c:154-182) reads ONLY `plan->lifetime`, `plan->transfer_compatible` and `plan->alignment`. It never reads `kind`, `role`, `operation`, `destination`, or `provenance` — those five fields are recorded into the block and into `res_pub.kind` and then ignored. Placement is therefore ONE hardcoded `if`: `pooled = !transfer_compatible && size+1 <= RES_POOL_MAX` (1 MiB) -> per-domain multipool, else `mi_malloc_aligned`/`mi_heap_malloc_aligned`. Models B (kind-major), D (role-split) and E (CxD) are literally inexpressible: there is no place to hang a per-kind or per-role arena and no routing function to select one. COMPLETE = a new module-private seam `src/resources/resources_place.h` + `resources_place.c` holding (i) a per-domain backing struct with a sparse arena table, (ii) a routing/planning function that consumes the WHOLE plan, and (iii) a vtable so a contestant is one TU, not an edit to the registry. Exact signatures I would introduce:

```c
// resources_place.h
typedef enum res_arena_id {
    RES_ARENA_METADATA = 0,   // rows, names, dep records, placement meta, control
    RES_ARENA_PAYLOAD_SMALL,  // variable payloads under the model's small_max
    RES_ARENA_PAYLOAD_BULK,   // large payloads
    RES_ARENA_CHUNK,          // fixed streaming chunks (ano_mem_pool)
    RES_ARENA_STRIPE,         // cache-striped SoA planes (ano_mem_stripe)
    RES_ARENA_STAGING,        // monotonic parse/ingest staging
    RES_ARENA_TRANSFER,       // externally transferable blocks
    RES_ARENA_COUNT
} res_arena_id;

typedef enum res_backing_kind {
    RES_BACK_MULTIPOOL = 1, RES_BACK_POOL, RES_BACK_MONOTONIC, RES_BACK_STRIPE, RES_BACK_HEAP
} res_backing_kind;

// One live lifetime domain's backing. root is the ONLY thing wink-out needs.
typedef struct res_backing {
    mi_heap_t *root;                 // every arena's parent chain bottoms out here
    void *arena[RES_ARENA_COUNT];    // concrete ano_mem_* handle, sparse; a model wires what it uses
    uint8_t  kindof[RES_ARENA_COUNT];// res_backing_kind per slot
    void *model_state;               // B: per-kind subtable. D/E: per-role subtable.
    ano_res_lifetime lifetime;
} res_backing;

// The routing decision. plan+size in, the exact home out. This function IS the contest.
typedef struct res_site {
    res_arena_id arena;
    uint8_t backing_kind;
    void *allocator;      // the ano_mem_multipool*/ano_mem_pool*/ano_mem_monotonic*/ano_mem_stripe*/mi_heap_t*
    size_t serving;       // what the arena will actually charge (asked, not recomputed)
    size_t alignment;     // what it will actually DELIVER (>= plan->alignment, or the plan is refused)
    bool   direct_landing;// an IO read / decoder may write straight into this block
    bool   transferable;  // may leave the manager without a copy or an interior free
} res_site;

typedef struct res_placement {
    const char *name;   // scaffold: "global-pool" | "scoped-pool". Stage B: "model-a".."model-e".
    int   (*open)(const struct res_placement *self, ano_res_lifetime lt, mi_heap_t *root, res_backing *out);
    void  (*wink)(const struct res_placement *self, res_backing *b);              // whole-domain teardown
    int   (*plan)(const struct res_placement *self, const res_backing *b,
                  const res_place_plan *plan, size_t size, res_site *out);        // route only, no alloc
    void *(*alloc)(const struct res_placement *self, res_backing *b, const res_site *site, size_t size);
    void  (*free) (const struct res_placement *self, res_backing *b, const res_site *site,
                   void *p, size_t size);
    ano_mem_stats (*stats)(const struct res_placement *self, const res_backing *b, res_arena_id arena);
} res_placement;

const res_placement *res_placement_active(void);   // selected once at registry init
const char          *res_placement_name(void);
```

`res_owned_block` (resources_internal.h:114-120) must carry `res_site site;` and lose the bare `bool pooled;` so a free routes back to the exact arena it came from. `res_domain` (resources_registry.c:65-73) collapses from `{mi_heap_t *heap; ano_mem_multipool *pool;}` to `{mi_heap_t *heap; res_backing backing;}`. NOTHING in include/anoptic_resources.h changes; `anores_t`, `ano_res_lifetime`, get/bytes/release/unload keep their exact shape — verified that src/resources/world/res_world.c, src/config/, src/keybindings/ and the renderer touch no placement symbol, so consumers are untouched by construction.

Allocation-DESTINATION planning does not exist; `res_destination` is a field nobody reads. Every small read pays a mandatory copy: `ano_res_get` (resources_registry.c:787-807) calls `res_read_all(NULL, ...)` which allocates on the DEFAULT heap (`mi_malloc_aligned`, resources_core.c:521-522), then `res_owned_alloc` the home, then `memcpy(home.data, staging, size+1)`, then `mi_free(staging)`. Same shape in `save_adopt` (resources_registry.c:1248-1252). COMPLETE = a two-verb allocation surface plus a destination-aware read primitive. The hard truth that must be designed around, not wished away: `res_read_all` believes only EOF (`rmos_size_hint` is a HINT — the remote-FS floor exists because 9P/SMB lie), and a multipool class block cannot grow in place. So 'read directly into home' is only sound as: plan a home from the hint, read into it, and on hint-lie SPILL to a re-planned home with exactly one charged copy. That copy is then a MEASURED property of the backend, which is the honest answer. Signatures:

```c
// resources_internal.h
int  res_owned_plan  (const res_place_plan *plan, size_t size, res_site *out);   // route, no alloc
int  res_owned_alloc (const res_place_plan *plan, size_t size, res_owned_block *out);
int  res_owned_stage (const res_place_plan *plan, size_t hint, res_owned_block *out); // RES_ARENA_STAGING
int  res_owned_commit(res_owned_block *staged, res_owned_block *home);  // 0 copies if same site, else 1 charged
void res_owned_free  (res_owned_block *block);

// resources_core.c: EOF-truth read into a caller-provided destination.
// The sink owns growth so the home block, the staging arena, or a pack-TOC-sized exact
// block are all expressible behind one read loop. res_read_all() becomes a thin wrapper.
typedef struct res_sink {
    void *ctx;
    void *(*reserve)(void *ctx, size_t hint, size_t *out_cap);   // may hand back the HOME block
    void *(*grow)   (void *ctx, size_t need, size_t *out_cap);   // hint lied: spill, charge one copy
    void  (*commit) (void *ctx, size_t final_size);
} res_sink;
int res_read_sink(const res_sink *sink, const char *abs, size_t *out_size);
```

With this, `RES_DEST_VARIABLE_PAYLOAD` lands in the payload multipool directly, `RES_DEST_BULK` lands in the bulk arena directly, `RES_DEST_STAGING` lands in the monotonic staging arena, and `RES_DEST_EXTERNAL_TRANSFER` lands in the transfer arena — the enum finally means something. Ripple: `res_read_all`'s current signature is used by `ano_res_get`, `ano_res_slurp` (resources_core.c:588), `save_probe_file` (resources_registry.c:1220) and `gfx_slurp` (res_graphics.c:118).

`ano_mem_stripe` does not exist. Confirmed: `git grep ano_mem_stripe -- src include` returns nothing; only `docs/resourcemgr/resourcemanager-real.md:371` describes it ('cache-line-striped placement for SoA side arrays. The speculative fourth; ships only with a consumer and a bench'). B.6 (Model D) requires 'bulk SoA arrays and ticket/consume planes use cache-striped placement' and B.7 (Model E) requires 'cache-striped SoA storage' INSIDE every lifetime domain. D and E cannot be built without it, and A.2 "Allocator roster" says omit no promised tool. COMPLETE = a fourth allocator in the pools tier, parent-composed like the other three so it winks out with the domain root, giving (a) lane-isolated allocation where two lanes never share a `ANO_THREAD_LINE` region, and (b) plane-set allocation where N parallel SoA arrays are carved from one parent acquisition with each plane base on the stripe grain. Signatures:

```c
// include/anoptic_memory_pools.h
typedef struct ano_mem_stripe ano_mem_stripe;

typedef struct ano_mem_stripe_cfg {
    size_t lanes;       // independently-written lanes; 0 = 1
    size_t grain;       // isolation distance; 0 = ANO_THREAD_LINE
    size_t chunk_hint;  // parent acquisition granularity; 0 = 64 KiB
} ano_mem_stripe_cfg;

ano_mem_stripe *ano_mem_stripe_make(ano_mem_parent parent, const ano_mem_stripe_cfg *cfg);

// size bytes owned by `lane`. Two different lanes never share a grain-sized region:
// lane writes cannot false-share. align 0 = the stripe grain. NULL on exhaustion. Never UB.
void *ano_mem_stripe_alloc(ano_mem_stripe *s, size_t lane, size_t size, size_t align);

// One SoA plane set: n_planes parallel arrays of `count` elements, elem_size[i] bytes each,
// every plane base on the grain, all from one parent acquisition so the set is contiguous
// and one prefetch stream per plane. 0 / -1. out_planes[i] receives plane i's base.
int ano_mem_stripe_planes(ano_mem_stripe *s, size_t count, const size_t *elem_size,
                          size_t n_planes, void **out_planes);

void ano_mem_stripe_reset(ano_mem_stripe *s);    // rewind, keep chunks (per-frame plane reuse)
void ano_mem_stripe_destroy(ano_mem_stripe *s);
ano_mem_stats ano_mem_stripe_stats(const ano_mem_stripe *s);
```

It ships with a resource consumer (`RES_ARENA_STRIPE` serving `RES_DEST_BULK` SoA scene planes, and in Stage C the ticket/consume planes) and a home bench, per the roster rule. A static assert must prove the grain is `ANO_THREAD_LINE` and that two lanes' bases differ by >= grain.

resources_os.h has no positional read, no advisory hint, and no cheap change-probe. Today: rmos_read_open/rmos_size_hint/rmos_read_chunk (stateful cursor)/rmos_read_close. Complete = three new seam ops, uniform across both TUs, keeping the header's stated doctrine (fresh handle per file; size_hint is a HINT; 0/-1 contracts).

  int rmos_read_at(rmos_file f, uint64_t offset, void *buf, size_t cap, size_t *got);
  typedef enum rmos_advice { RMOS_ADVICE_SEQUENTIAL=1, RMOS_ADVICE_RANDOM, RMOS_ADVICE_WILLNEED } rmos_advice;
  int rmos_advise(rmos_file f, uint64_t offset, uint64_t len, rmos_advice a);
  int rmos_stat_hint(const char *abs, uint64_t *mtime, uint64_t *size);   // ADVISORY ONLY

rmos_read_at contract, and it is the whole ballgame: *got==0 is the ONLY EOF signal; 0 < *got < cap is a SHORT READ, not EOF (9P/SMB do this routinely) and the CALLER must loop. Never fold the loop into the seam, because the loop's termination rule differs between 'read to EOF' (res_read_all) and 'deliver exactly len' (res_read_range).
POSIX: pread(2), retry on EINTR. Win64: ReadFile with an OVERLAPPED carrying Offset/OffsetHigh on the ordinary synchronous handle -- this is positional and blocking, but per MSDN it ALSO advances the file pointer as a side effect, so one handle is single-owner in Stage A. Record that in the header comment; the signature is already the one Stage C needs (Stage C opens per-worker handles or flips to FILE_FLAG_OVERLAPPED+event without re-signaturing).
rmos_advise: posix_fadvise on Linux; F_RDAHEAD/F_RDADVISE or no-op-0 on macOS; no-op-0 on Windows (the equivalent is FILE_FLAG_SEQUENTIAL_SCAN at open). Advisory: a failure is never load-bearing.
rmos_stat_hint: mtime as an opaque u64 (ns where available). Marked ADVISORY in the header exactly like rmos_size_hint -- hot reload uses it ONLY as a cheap filter and confirms with a content hash.
RMOS_CHUNK_MAX (512 KiB, already defined at resources_os.h:29) stays and becomes the chunk-pool block size; do not introduce a second constant.

No bounded chunk pool exists and ano_mem_pool has no production consumer at all (the spec calls this out twice: A.2 'Allocator roster', A.2 'Streaming economy'). Create src/resources/resources_stream.c + declarations in resources_internal.h. It owns THE chunk pool and the three primitives everything downstream needs.

The pool: one process-wide ano_mem_pool over the resources module heap, block_size = RMOS_CHUNK_MAX (512 KiB), block_align = ANO_CACHE_LINE, max_blocks = RES_CHUNK_POOL_MAX (8), ano_mem_pool_reserve(2) at init, destroyed in res_stream_shutdown. Created/destroyed on the init/owner thread (ano_mem_pool is single-owner, per anoptic_memory_pools.h:32-34).

The pool must have REAL work or it is the scaffolding this plan forbids. Its three genuine consumers, all landed here:
  1. codec staging -- compressed frame in, decode straight into the destination (a raw ranged read needs no chunk: rmos_read_at writes into dst directly; do not fake a copy to justify the pool);
  2. res_hash_file -- fold FNV-1a-64 over a whole file 512 KiB at a time with no full-payload allocation (hot-reload confirmation, builder payload hashes, TOC hashing);
  3. the builder's streaming copy of payloads into the pack.

Primitives:
  int res_read_range(const char *abs, uint64_t off, size_t len, void *dst);   // exactly len or fail
  int res_hash_file(const char *abs, uint64_t *out_hash, uint64_t *out_size);
  void *res_chunk_acquire(void);  void res_chunk_release(void *chunk);

res_read_range MUST distinguish three outcomes with three codes: 0 = exactly len delivered; RES_RANGE_EOF = the file ended before len (range past EOF -- a caller error, not an IO error); -1/-2 = open/IO failure (matching res_read_all's existing -1 open-failure vs -2 mid-file-failure convention, which the mount walk depends on: -1 means 'try the next root', -2 means 'stop'). A silent short return is the exact byte-truth violation A.2 forbids.
Exhaustion: ano_mem_pool_alloc returns NULL when capped-and-empty (false-on-empty, never blocks). The synchronous path degrades to one mi_malloc_aligned chunk charged to stats (never blocks, never fails the read) -- and the test forces it by building a pool with max_blocks=1 and running two nested consumers.
Account pool chunk_bytes/chunk_count into ano_res_stats (the fields already exist in ano_res_allocator_stats).

There is no ranged read on the public surface; ano_res_get (resources_registry.c:756) is whole-file-only and every load calls res_read_all into a default-heap staging buffer, then memcpy's into the home block (resources_registry.c:787-807) -- one full copy per load that the ranged/pack path must not inherit. Add to include/anoptic_resources.h, in the existing lifetime+read-scope grammar:

  // Exactly len bytes at offset from the winning source (loose or pack). dst is the caller's.
  // Short-at-EOF is a refusal, never a silent partial. Output: 0, or negative.
  int ano_res_read_range(const char *logical, uint64_t offset, size_t len, void *dst);

  // Own only [offset, offset+len) under lifetime, keyed "<logical>#<offset>+<len>".
  // Serves through the same anores_t / ano_res_bytes / read-scope grammar as any resource.
  anores_t ano_res_get_range(ano_res_lifetime lifetime, const char *logical,
                             uint64_t offset, size_t len);

The '#' key suffix is legal under the existing path grammar (byte_ok, resources_core.c:108) and matches the derived-key convention res_graphics already uses ("<source>#gfx", res_graphics.c:348).
While here, kill the staging copy on the owned path: res_owned_alloc FIRST, then read (or decode) directly into home.data. A.2 'Allocation path' demands exactly this, and the packed+codec path has nowhere sane to put a staging buffer anyway. Keep res_account_copy honest -- if a copy survives, it must still be counted.
Note for the audio squad: streaming audio ranged reads land on RAW (already-compressed) payloads, which the builder stores raw, so ranged+packed works for them. Ranged reads INTO an LZ4/zstd-compressed entry are an explicit Stage A non-goal (see codec-seam-lz4).

No codec exists. Vendor LZ4 into external/lz4/ (owner decision: default ON) as lib/lz4.c + lz4.h + lib/lz4hc.c + lz4hc.h (BSD-2; four files, fits 'no heavyweight deps'). Upstream ships no minimal CMake tree at that path, so hand-write external/lz4/CMakeLists.txt (~6 lines, target_sources onto anoptic_core), mirroring how jsmn/stb are pulled in at CMakeLists.txt:127-141. Add the ATTRIBUTIONS.md entry. lz4hc is builder-only but compiles into core (small; the alternative -- a separate lib -- buys nothing).

The seam, module-private, so no codec symbol escapes src/resources/ (same law that keeps cgltf/stb_image inside graphics/):
  src/resources/codec/res_codec.h + res_codec.c
  typedef enum res_codec { RES_CODEC_RAW=0, RES_CODEC_LZ4=1, RES_CODEC_ZSTD=2, RES_CODEC_GDEFLATE=3 } res_codec;
  bool   res_codec_available(res_codec c);
  size_t res_codec_bound(res_codec c, size_t src_len);
  int    res_codec_encode(res_codec c, const void *src, size_t n, void *dst, size_t *dst_cap_inout);
  int    res_codec_decode(res_codec c, const void *src, size_t n, void *dst, size_t dst_len);

Decode MUST use LZ4_decompress_safe (NEVER LZ4_decompress_fast -- pack bytes are untrusted input and _fast is a remote memory-corruption primitive) and MUST require the produced length to equal dst_len exactly; anything else is corruption, return -1.
Framing, and get this right or the Stage C overlap has nowhere to live: a compressed entry payload is a sequence of frames, each `u32 csize_le` + csize bytes, each decoding to exactly RES_CODEC_CHUNK uncompressed bytes (last frame = remainder). RES_CODEC_CHUNK = 496 KiB, NOT 512: LZ4_COMPRESSBOUND(496K) = 496K + 496K/255 + 16 ~= 498 KiB, which fits inside one 512 KiB pooled chunk. A 512 KiB uncompressed chunk has a 514 KiB bound and does NOT fit -- that arithmetic is the trap.
Stage A non-goal, stated explicitly so nobody ships a broken seek: ranged reads into an LZ4/zstd entry are unsupported (sequential frames carry no random-access index). Compressed entries are whole-entry loads; ranged reads work on RAW entries and loose files. Already-compressed assets (audio, PNG/JPEG) are stored RAW by builder policy, so the streaming shape is unaffected.
Store-raw bypass rule, and it must be a pure function of the bytes: if csize >= size - size/64 (>=98.4% of original), store RAW.

No builder exists. Split it so the tests can drive it in-process and the house rules still hold (an offline tool may not reach into resources_internal.h from outside the module):
  include/anoptic_res_pack.h:  int ano_res_pack_build(const char *src_dir, const char *out_pack);
  src/resources/pack/res_pack_build.c:  the ~250-line builder, compiled into anoptic_core.
  tools/anopak/main.c:  a ~40-line argv wrapper. add_executable(anopak ...) linking anoptic_core.
Determinism is the merge bar -- byte-identical output for identical input, proven by building twice and memcmp'ing:
  - input walk collects logical paths, then sorts them BYTEWISE (rmos_scan_dir order is explicitly unspecified, resources_os.h:83);
  - entries sorted ascending by rid; an rid collision is a HARD ERROR with both paths named, exit nonzero (the runtime bsearch assumes uniqueness and the registry already refuses collisions);
  - payloads written in rid order, each at a 4096-aligned offset, padding explicitly zero-filled;
  - codec choice is a pure function of extension policy + the store-raw rule (csize >= size - size/64), never of mtime, locale, rand, or thread order;
  - NO timestamps anywhere in the file;
  - saves/ is EXCLUDED from the input walk (save generations are user data under the write root and are never packed -- same exclusion the temp GC already makes at resources_core.c:300).
Builder verifies every entry it writes: decode it back and check payload_hash before the pack is renamed into place. Write the pack itself through res_write_protocol (resources_core.c:613) so a killed builder never leaves a half-pack that mounts.

Hot reload needs to swap a live row's payload in place, and the registry cannot do it. publish_locked (resources_registry.c:491) only binds a pub for an unbound row. ano_res_release (resources_registry.c:854-862) does store-NULL-then-restore-on-stall -- a reload MUST NOT do that, because a reader that acquire-loads during the NULL window sees a sentinel for a resource that is fully live, breaking the 'old-complete or new-complete, never a mixed object and never a spurious miss' contract (C.10).

Add, in resources_registry.c, reusing the epoch machinery that ALREADY EXISTS (queue_retire_locked:424, reader_safe:409, collect_locked:450, res_retired list) -- do not invent a second reclamation scheme:
  static int republish_locked(uint32_t slot, res_row *row, res_owned_block *new_block);
  // 1. build the new immutable res_pub for new_block with generation+1
  // 2. ONE release-store of the new pub over the old (never NULL in between)
  // 3. queue_retire_locked(old_pub, old_block) at the bumped retire epoch
  // 4. collect_locked() reclaims only after every reader lane registered before the swap is quiescent
Also add to res_row (resources_registry.c:46): uint64_t content_hash and the winning res_source identity (kind + which mount index), both recorded at load. Hot reload cannot work without them and they belong to the row, not to a side table.
Generation contract, and the renderer squad must be told: a reload BUMPS row->generation, so handles held across a reload resolve to the sentinel. The alternative (stable gen, swapped data) would hand a reader a pointer whose bytes change underneath it. ano_res_reload_poll therefore returns the changed rids and consumers re-get.
